00:35:25.290 --> 00:35:26.000
HADLEY FREEMAN: Yeah, Yeah.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:26.155
Absolutely.

00:35:26.155 --> 00:35:26.780
No question.

00:35:26.780 --> 00:35:30.164
JON SKEET: And by the time we've
got "Wonder Woman" and "Black

00:35:30.164 --> 00:35:33.860
Panther" and at the same
time, young people certainly

00:35:33.860 --> 00:35:35.690
in America and I
think over in the UK

00:35:35.690 --> 00:35:39.070
as well to a slightly
lesser extent, appear

00:35:39.070 --> 00:35:40.310
to be more politically aware.

00:35:40.310 --> 00:35:41.690
HADLEY FREEMAN:
Yes, no question.

00:35:41.690 --> 00:35:43.754
JON SKEET: Is there a
correlation, causation?

00:35:43.754 --> 00:35:45.170
HADLEY FREEMAN: I
mean, it may be.

00:35:45.170 --> 00:35:46.550
I mean, it's certainly
true that superhero movies

00:35:46.550 --> 00:35:48.740
have been good at
smuggling in good roles

00:35:48.740 --> 00:35:51.054
for women and ethnic minorities.

00:35:51.054 --> 00:35:52.220
They have been good at that.

00:35:52.220 --> 00:35:54.590
In "Ghostbusters," one
of the specific things

00:35:54.590 --> 00:35:57.987
was to improve the
representation of--

00:35:57.987 --> 00:35:59.570
this is a terrible
way of putting it--

00:35:59.570 --> 00:36:00.800
the black Ghostbuster.

00:36:00.800 --> 00:36:02.758
I mean, one of the big
faults with the original

00:36:02.758 --> 00:36:05.230
"Ghostbusters" is how Ernie
Hudson is so sidelined in it,

00:36:05.230 --> 00:36:06.110
like for no reason.

00:36:06.110 --> 00:36:08.440
Either have a minute or don't.

00:36:08.440 --> 00:36:12.050
And oh, god, Leslie, what
is her name who plays her

00:36:12.050 --> 00:36:13.610
in the new "Ghostbusters"?

00:36:13.610 --> 00:36:14.810
My mind's just gone blank.

00:36:14.810 --> 00:36:16.160
Can someone google it for me?

00:36:16.160 --> 00:36:19.070
Anyway, she has a
real role in it,

00:36:19.070 --> 00:36:23.120
and she's in it the whole
movie, and she's not pushed out.

00:36:23.120 --> 00:36:24.090
And that is great.

00:36:24.090 --> 00:36:24.860
That was great.

00:36:24.860 --> 00:36:25.580
And definitely young people--

00:36:25.580 --> 00:36:27.830
I don't know if it's
because of superhero movies

00:36:27.830 --> 00:36:29.030
that young people
are more in line.

00:36:29.030 --> 00:36:30.946
I think young people
always need to go further

00:36:30.946 --> 00:36:32.150
than the generation before.

00:36:32.150 --> 00:36:34.640
And young people are going
further in this than we did.

00:36:34.640 --> 00:36:36.380
JON SKEET: Right.

00:36:36.380 --> 00:36:37.880
And another thing
I find interesting

00:36:37.880 --> 00:36:42.320
about superhero films,
you talked about "Batman,"

00:36:42.320 --> 00:36:45.465
even though it was dark in a
way, it had huge light moments.

00:36:45.465 --> 00:36:46.340
HADLEY FREEMAN: What?

00:36:46.340 --> 00:36:47.427
Tim Burton or?

00:36:47.427 --> 00:36:48.510
JON SKEET: The Tim Burton.

00:36:48.510 --> 00:36:48.980
HADLEY FREEMAN:
The Tim Burton one.

00:36:48.980 --> 00:36:49.940
Yeah.

00:36:49.940 --> 00:36:53.841
JON SKEET: So big Gothic
feeling, but still hugely funny

00:36:53.841 --> 00:36:54.340
bits.

00:36:54.340 --> 00:36:55.430
HADLEY FREEMAN: Yeah.

00:36:55.430 --> 00:36:59.120
JON SKEET: And when you
wrote the book was before--

00:36:59.120 --> 00:37:00.320
I think before "Deadpool."

00:37:00.320 --> 00:37:01.160
HADLEY FREEMAN: Yes, it was.

00:37:01.160 --> 00:37:02.690
JON SKEET: Definitely
before "Thor Ragnarok."

00:37:02.690 --> 00:37:03.860
HADLEY FREEMAN:
Yeah, that's right.

00:37:03.860 --> 00:37:04.880
JON SKEET: Do you
feel that things

00:37:04.880 --> 00:37:06.080
are taking an upswing there?

00:37:06.080 --> 00:37:06.860
HADLEY FREEMAN: I think so.

00:37:06.860 --> 00:37:07.460
And it's weird.

00:37:07.460 --> 00:37:08.834
I've seen actors
like Chris Pratt

00:37:08.834 --> 00:37:10.800
or whoever get more in
these kind of roles.

00:37:10.800 --> 00:37:14.510
And they are funny rather
than tortured Christian Bale

00:37:14.510 --> 00:37:16.760
and tortured Tom Hardy
with the mask on his face.

00:37:16.760 --> 00:37:17.802
I mean, I honestly--

00:37:17.802 --> 00:37:20.010
do you guys all like those
movies, the modern Batman?

00:37:20.010 --> 00:37:22.200
JON SKEET: I loved them,
but I didn't laugh at them.

00:37:22.200 --> 00:37:25.220
Whereas we recently rewatched
"Ragnarok" and it's hilarious.

00:37:25.220 --> 00:37:25.970
HADLEY FREEMAN: It's very funny.

00:37:25.970 --> 00:37:26.660
It's very funny.

00:37:26.660 --> 00:37:27.380
No, it's true.

00:37:27.380 --> 00:37:32.540
I mean, I loved the modern
Christian Bale Batman

00:37:32.540 --> 00:37:33.440
with the Joker.

00:37:33.440 --> 00:37:35.370
I mean, that is a
great role, obviously,

00:37:35.370 --> 00:37:36.890
with Heath Ledger as the Joker.

00:37:36.890 --> 00:37:38.930
But it's not a fun watch.

00:37:38.930 --> 00:37:41.240
I mean, it's quite heavy
weather, really, watching it.

00:37:41.240 --> 00:37:42.510
And everything is so dark.

00:37:42.510 --> 00:37:44.120
I mean, not just like mood.

00:37:44.120 --> 00:37:46.550
I mean, the lighting, you
can't fricking see anything.

00:37:46.550 --> 00:37:50.420
Whereas you watch Tim Burton,
I mean, it's so much fun.

00:37:50.420 --> 00:37:53.330
And watching Jack Nicholson
do his little dance

00:37:53.330 --> 00:37:55.310
down the steps
towards Kim Basinger,

00:37:55.310 --> 00:37:59.260
he's playing Prince on
his boom box, so much fun.

00:37:59.260 --> 00:38:00.950
And it looks like a cartoon.

00:38:00.950 --> 00:38:03.890
It doesn't look like it's
taking itself so damn seriously.

00:38:03.890 --> 00:38:05.870
And it doesn't have
the constant car

00:38:05.870 --> 00:38:08.660
chases like you have with
the Christian Bale ones.

00:38:08.660 --> 00:38:10.070
And the Christian
Bale Batmans, I

00:38:10.070 --> 00:38:11.000
don't mean to keep
knocking them.

00:38:11.000 --> 00:38:12.500
Obviously, they're
beautiful and they're

00:38:12.500 --> 00:38:13.541
done in this amazing way.

00:38:13.541 --> 00:38:15.840
Christopher Nolan is obviously
an incredible filmmaker.

00:38:15.840 --> 00:38:17.290
But there is just too much.

00:38:17.290 --> 00:38:18.506
There's just too much.

00:38:18.506 --> 00:38:20.630
I feel there's too many
characters, too many people

00:38:20.630 --> 00:38:23.030
being tortured,
emotionally tortured.

00:38:23.030 --> 00:38:24.320
You know you have Gary Oldman.

00:38:24.320 --> 00:38:25.160
You have Christian Bale.

00:38:25.160 --> 00:38:26.240
You have whoever the villain is.

00:38:26.240 --> 00:38:27.240
You have this and that.

00:38:27.240 --> 00:38:29.110
JON SKEET: And it
became more so, I think.

00:38:29.110 --> 00:38:29.510
HADLEY FREEMAN: Yeah.

00:38:29.510 --> 00:38:31.160
JON SKEET: So by the time you
get to "Dark Knight Rises"--

00:38:31.160 --> 00:38:32.250
HADLEY FREEMAN: Oh my god.

00:38:32.250 --> 00:38:34.250
JON SKEET: It's really all
on for a very long time.

00:38:34.250 --> 00:38:34.890
HADLEY FREEMAN: It's so long.

00:38:34.890 --> 00:38:36.598
And like Avengers,
there's just too much.

00:38:36.598 --> 00:38:38.660
They pack in so much
in these movies.

00:38:38.660 --> 00:38:40.810
Whereas I feel like with
Tim Burton's "Batman,"

00:38:40.810 --> 00:38:43.330
you have just nice, clean
Michael Keaton a bit unhappy

00:38:43.330 --> 00:38:45.990
in a castle, some
villain, the end.

00:38:45.990 --> 00:38:47.240
JON SKEET: There is the angst.

00:38:47.240 --> 00:38:48.614
HADLEY FREEMAN:
Yeah, oh, there's

00:38:48.614 --> 00:38:52.380
angst, but angst in a quite
interesting self-mocking way.

00:38:52.380 --> 00:38:55.350
Like he knows he's
this pathetic rich boy.

00:38:55.350 --> 00:38:57.170
Like, feel sorry
for me rich boy.

00:38:57.170 --> 00:39:00.000
Whereas Christian Bale
is just miserable.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:01.680
"This is a great night out."

00:39:04.082 --> 00:39:05.790
JON SKEET: Do we have
any other questions

00:39:05.790 --> 00:39:08.021
so I can be slightly
less self-indulgent?

00:39:11.037 --> 00:39:13.120
AUDIENCE: I used to work
in children's publishing,

00:39:13.120 --> 00:39:15.090
and I went once to a
marvelous showcase,

00:39:15.090 --> 00:39:18.230
and I was really excited,
because I'm a big Marvel fan.

00:39:18.230 --> 00:39:21.240
And I remember being incredibly
disappointed because they

00:39:21.240 --> 00:39:23.010
had this huge cinema
screen, and they were

00:39:23.010 --> 00:39:24.540
showing all their new films.

00:39:24.540 --> 00:39:27.570
And then it came up in massive
letters "Everything we do

00:39:27.570 --> 00:39:29.950
is to--" and I was just
really excited for it--

00:39:29.950 --> 00:39:31.720
And it said "To
sell more product."

00:39:31.720 --> 00:39:32.970
And I remember just thinking--

00:39:32.970 --> 00:39:34.070
HADLEY FREEMAN: Whoa, yay!

00:39:34.070 --> 00:39:36.750
AUDIENCE: --Is that what's
happening to cinema today

00:39:36.750 --> 00:39:40.500
that they want to basically
make everything PG-12 so they

00:39:40.500 --> 00:39:42.570
can appeal to as many
people as possible?

00:39:42.570 --> 00:39:42.910
HADLEY FREEMAN: Yeah.

00:39:42.910 --> 00:39:44.993
AUDIENCE: And that's why
I think films like Batman

00:39:44.993 --> 00:39:46.805
don't work anymore,
because they're darker

00:39:46.805 --> 00:39:48.180
and they're older,
and everything

00:39:48.180 --> 00:39:50.722
feels a little bit safer, and
we don't have many 18s anymore.

00:39:50.722 --> 00:39:52.513
I remember when I used
to go to the cinema,

00:39:52.513 --> 00:39:54.470
I used to sneak into
18s all the time.

00:39:54.470 --> 00:39:56.340
And it's now like
there's no 18s.

00:39:56.340 --> 00:39:58.520
Everything's really
dry, and everything

00:39:58.520 --> 00:40:01.100
is trying to sell more
product and merchandise,

00:40:01.100 --> 00:40:03.070
and I wondered if
you shared that.

00:40:03.070 --> 00:40:03.370
HADLEY FREEMAN: I
mean, definitely

00:40:03.370 --> 00:40:05.078
everything is trying
to sell merchandise,

00:40:05.078 --> 00:40:07.140
but you have to blame
'80s movies for that.

00:40:07.140 --> 00:40:09.090
I mean, it was the '80s movies
that really got onto that.

00:40:09.090 --> 00:40:10.590
Obviously, "Star
Wars" in the '70s

00:40:10.590 --> 00:40:12.930
and then "Batman" in the
'80s and "Ghostbusters".

00:40:12.930 --> 00:40:16.170
But I don't feel like they
were just made for that.

00:40:16.170 --> 00:40:17.970
They weren't seen as
vehicles for that.

00:40:17.970 --> 00:40:20.520
It was the merchandise came off
the greatness of the movies.

00:40:20.520 --> 00:40:23.019
And actually, the merchandise
just kind of took those movies

00:40:23.019 --> 00:40:24.510
by surprise, I feel.

00:40:24.510 --> 00:40:28.260
Whereas now the movie is
almost a sideshow to everything

00:40:28.260 --> 00:40:29.310
around it.

00:40:29.310 --> 00:40:31.990
There's just not as much effort
put into scripts anymore,

00:40:31.990 --> 00:40:34.185
is, for me, the real
problem between movies

00:40:34.185 --> 00:40:35.730
today and movies in the '80s.

00:40:35.730 --> 00:40:38.760
And that's because so
much of a movie's takings

00:40:38.760 --> 00:40:40.620
comes from overseas,
that they don't

00:40:40.620 --> 00:40:42.870
want to have movies that
have complicated scripts that

00:40:42.870 --> 00:40:46.200
need a lot of translation, where
things have cultural references

00:40:46.200 --> 00:40:48.610
that won't translate overseas.

00:40:48.610 --> 00:40:51.060
Which is why movies now, like,
for example the Christopher

00:40:51.060 --> 00:40:54.960
Nolan Batmans are so full
of car chases and shootouts

00:40:54.960 --> 00:40:56.100
and special effects.

00:40:56.100 --> 00:40:58.308
Because obviously, you don't
need to translate those.

00:40:58.308 --> 00:41:00.890
I mean, whereas you have
something like going back

00:41:00.890 --> 00:41:03.870
to Tim Burton's Batmans, there's
a lot of dialogue going on

00:41:03.870 --> 00:41:06.450
in those movies, whether
it's in the newspaper office

00:41:06.450 --> 00:41:09.450
or whether it's
Bruce talking, having

00:41:09.450 --> 00:41:12.450
the long conversations with his
butler and these weird parties

00:41:12.450 --> 00:41:13.050
that he had.

00:41:13.050 --> 00:41:15.720
There's emotional stuff
that needs translating.

00:41:15.720 --> 00:41:17.940
And it's just too
much of a faff.

00:41:17.940 --> 00:41:19.560
And like, why bother?

00:41:19.560 --> 00:41:22.776
Big CGI effects
work well anywhere.

00:41:22.776 --> 00:41:24.900
Although I personally find
them incredibly tedious.

00:41:24.900 --> 00:41:26.775
One of the things I love
about "Ghostbusters"

00:41:26.775 --> 00:41:28.770
is how charming the
special effects are.

00:41:28.770 --> 00:41:30.840
They're so shonky.

00:41:30.840 --> 00:41:33.390
And now when I see special
effects in a movie--

00:41:33.390 --> 00:41:35.562
I went to see the
modern "Jungle Book,"

00:41:35.562 --> 00:41:37.020
I'm watching the
actors thinking "I

00:41:37.020 --> 00:41:39.690
know you're just standing
against a blue screen."

00:41:39.690 --> 00:41:41.100
That's all that's
happening here.

00:41:41.100 --> 00:41:44.650
You feel no real connection
between what's going on,

00:41:44.650 --> 00:41:47.254
the actor and the special
effects, I don't think.

00:41:47.254 --> 00:41:49.170
And I think that's
something that's been lost,

00:41:49.170 --> 00:41:50.670
but that's what
translates overseas.

00:41:54.090 --> 00:41:56.260
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:41:56.260 --> 00:41:58.390
Do you also have lessons
that we shouldn't

00:41:58.390 --> 00:41:59.640
have learned from '80s movies?

00:41:59.640 --> 00:42:01.390
HADLEY FREEMAN: Oh my
goodness, of course.

00:42:01.390 --> 00:42:03.085
So obviously '80s
movies, for all

00:42:03.085 --> 00:42:05.190
I'm talking about
Eddie Murphy, etc, etc,

00:42:05.190 --> 00:42:07.322
were completely, totally racist.

00:42:07.322 --> 00:42:09.280
Which is why it's amazing
that Eddie Murphy was

00:42:09.280 --> 00:42:12.250
such a success, which is another
reason why everyone should just

00:42:12.250 --> 00:42:14.890
worship his talent.

00:42:14.890 --> 00:42:15.659
If you look at--

00:42:15.659 --> 00:42:17.950
I mean, let's see, what's
the worst '80s racist movies?

00:42:17.950 --> 00:42:18.910
I mean, where to even begin?

00:42:18.910 --> 00:42:20.650
Obviously, there's
"Sixteen Candles,"

00:42:20.650 --> 00:42:23.652
which is John Hughes' first
film with Molly Ringwald, who's

00:42:23.652 --> 00:42:26.110
upset because her parents have
forgotten her 16th birthday.

00:42:26.110 --> 00:42:28.165
What an innocent sweet
movie, you might think.

00:42:28.165 --> 00:42:31.210
Ah, but let me tell you about
their random Asian exchange

00:42:31.210 --> 00:42:34.780
student called Long Duk
Dong, who just once had

00:42:34.780 --> 00:42:37.420
sex with a white girl and does
things like fall out of trees

00:42:37.420 --> 00:42:39.250
at inopportune moments.

00:42:39.250 --> 00:42:41.380
There's also this
unbelievably weird bit

00:42:41.380 --> 00:42:45.043
in "Sixteen Candles,"
where the boy who

00:42:45.043 --> 00:42:48.310
Molly Ringwald's in
love with is talking

00:42:48.310 --> 00:42:51.110
about how his girlfriend
has passed out at a party,

00:42:51.110 --> 00:42:53.110
and he could have, quote,
unquote, "Had her five

00:42:53.110 --> 00:42:55.930
times without her noticing,"
and then tells the school

00:42:55.930 --> 00:43:00.039
nurse, who is played by
Anthony Michael Hall,

00:43:00.039 --> 00:43:02.580
"Why don't you just go out in
the car and have sex with her?"

00:43:02.580 --> 00:43:03.490
He doesn't say in those words.

00:43:03.490 --> 00:43:05.050
He goes, "why don't
you go upstairs?"

00:43:05.050 --> 00:43:06.220
And he does.

00:43:06.220 --> 00:43:08.950
And then the girl wakes
up next to this dorky guy.

00:43:08.950 --> 00:43:10.524
And she's like,
"Did we have sex?"

00:43:10.524 --> 00:43:11.440
And he goes, "Uh-huh."

00:43:11.440 --> 00:43:13.480
And she's like, "Oh, hi."

00:43:13.480 --> 00:43:15.820
It's the most weird
thing in the world.

00:43:15.820 --> 00:43:17.870
And '80s movies are full
of that kind of stuff.

00:43:17.870 --> 00:43:20.430
I mean, those kind
of movies don't get--

00:43:20.430 --> 00:43:21.640
they haven't lasted so well.

00:43:21.640 --> 00:43:23.260
Things like "Porky's."

00:43:23.260 --> 00:43:25.540
"Risky Business" is something
that everyone remembers

00:43:25.540 --> 00:43:27.880
very fondly as this movie
in which Tom Cruise danced

00:43:27.880 --> 00:43:28.762
in his underpants.

00:43:28.762 --> 00:43:30.220
But actually, if
you watch it, it's

00:43:30.220 --> 00:43:35.059
a movie about how a boy
becomes a pimp, becomes a pimp

00:43:35.059 --> 00:43:36.850
and then gets into
Princeton because of it.

00:43:36.850 --> 00:43:39.190
Because a Princeton
guy comes to his house

00:43:39.190 --> 00:43:42.675
to meet Tom Cruise, who is
now fully a pimp, and probably

00:43:42.675 --> 00:43:44.800
sleeps with the hookers
that he keeps in his house,

00:43:44.800 --> 00:43:46.210
and then gets him
into Princeton.

00:43:46.210 --> 00:43:48.418
It's the weirdest movie
you'll ever see in your life,

00:43:48.418 --> 00:43:49.929
I swear to God.

00:43:49.929 --> 00:43:51.220
So there's all that, obviously.

00:43:51.220 --> 00:43:53.500
And also racism
against black people

00:43:53.500 --> 00:43:55.096
is so obvious in '80s movies.

00:43:55.096 --> 00:43:56.470
I mean, Eddie
Murphy's first film

00:43:56.470 --> 00:43:59.410
was "48 Hours," in which
he's opposite Nick Nolte.

00:43:59.410 --> 00:44:02.080
And Eddie Murphy
plays this con who's

00:44:02.080 --> 00:44:04.150
let out of prison to
help grizzled cop Nick

00:44:04.150 --> 00:44:07.370
Nolte find a criminal ring,
if I remember this correctly.

00:44:07.370 --> 00:44:07.964
It was actually it
was actually supposed

00:44:07.964 --> 00:44:10.297
to be Richard Pryor who was
supposed to be in the movie,

00:44:10.297 --> 00:44:11.815
but he was too
much of a disaster,

00:44:11.815 --> 00:44:13.480
so they cast Eddie instead.

00:44:13.480 --> 00:44:16.890
Now, Nick Nolte is playing
the traditional grizzled cop.

00:44:16.890 --> 00:44:20.080
A bit alcoholic,
has woman problems.

00:44:20.080 --> 00:44:22.360
And as part of his
charming grizzledness,

00:44:22.360 --> 00:44:24.130
he is incredibly racist.

00:44:24.130 --> 00:44:28.480
And he calls Eddie Murphy
things like watermelon, a spear

00:44:28.480 --> 00:44:29.380
chucker.

00:44:29.380 --> 00:44:30.930
Unbelievably racist terms.

00:44:30.930 --> 00:44:33.850
And at no point is this
seen as like, "Oh, maybe we

00:44:33.850 --> 00:44:35.200
shouldn't like this guy."

00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:37.630
It's seen as part of
his charming, unreformed

00:44:37.630 --> 00:44:38.890
grizzledness.

00:44:38.890 --> 00:44:42.530
And Eddie Murphy was asked about
this in a couple of interviews.

00:44:42.530 --> 00:44:44.770
"Was this not a bit weird
for you to be doing?"

00:44:44.770 --> 00:44:48.040
And he's like, "Well, you
know, because my character is

00:44:48.040 --> 00:44:50.177
equal with him it makes it OK."

00:44:50.177 --> 00:44:51.760
And you're like,
"No, what makes it OK

00:44:51.760 --> 00:44:55.000
is that Eddie Murphy is such
a charismatic actor that he

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:58.420
doesn't feel totally
subjugated by it."

00:44:58.420 --> 00:45:01.360
He out-acts Nick Nolte
and steals all the scenes.

00:45:01.360 --> 00:45:03.940
But when you watch it, you're
like, "This is disgusting.

00:45:03.940 --> 00:45:05.440
And why am I supposed
to be cheering

00:45:05.440 --> 00:45:07.540
on this grizzled,
old, racist cop who's

00:45:07.540 --> 00:45:09.640
being totally racist?"

00:45:09.640 --> 00:45:12.190
So there's obviously
tons of that.

00:45:12.190 --> 00:45:15.457
And also when you look at
Eddie Murphy's movies, I mean,

00:45:15.457 --> 00:45:17.040
I'm sorry to be going
on about Murphy.

00:45:17.040 --> 00:45:19.360
It does happen.

00:45:19.360 --> 00:45:22.689
He was not allowed to do
very much within, really.

00:45:22.689 --> 00:45:24.230
I mean, even when
he was making them.

00:45:24.230 --> 00:45:26.302
So you look at "Beverly
Hills Cop," for example,

00:45:26.302 --> 00:45:28.510
which was a movie that was
written for a white actor.

00:45:28.510 --> 00:45:31.827
Incredibly, it was supposed to
be Mickey Rourke who was in it.

00:45:31.827 --> 00:45:33.910
And then it was supposed
to be Sylvester Stallone.

00:45:33.910 --> 00:45:34.870
Ugh.

00:45:34.870 --> 00:45:39.020
And then to Don Simpson
and Jerry Bruckheimer

00:45:39.020 --> 00:45:41.155
has enormous credit,
who are producers,

00:45:41.155 --> 00:45:43.280
they did something that
had never been done before,

00:45:43.280 --> 00:45:45.190
which is they decided
to cast a black actor

00:45:45.190 --> 00:45:48.022
in a white character's
role, and they cast Eddie.

00:45:48.022 --> 00:45:49.480
Yet when you're
watching this, it's

00:45:49.480 --> 00:45:51.145
very notable that
Eddie Murphy's not

00:45:51.145 --> 00:45:53.500
allowed to have sex, really,
at any point in this movie.

00:45:53.500 --> 00:45:55.660
He has this white female
friend in Beverly Hills

00:45:55.660 --> 00:45:57.002
who works in the art gallery.

00:45:57.002 --> 00:45:58.960
I'm sure all you have
seen "Beverly Hills Cop."

00:45:58.960 --> 00:46:01.180
You know the girl who
works in the art gallery.

00:46:01.180 --> 00:46:04.250
She's got that assistant with
the funny accent, Bronson

00:46:04.250 --> 00:46:05.290
Pinchot.

00:46:05.290 --> 00:46:07.862
And there are lots of scenes
where this girl's sprawling

00:46:07.862 --> 00:46:09.070
on his bed in the hotel room.

00:46:09.070 --> 00:46:10.530
They're hanging
out in hotel rooms.

00:46:10.530 --> 00:46:11.800
They're old friends.

00:46:11.800 --> 00:46:14.650
And clearly, in the
original script,

00:46:14.650 --> 00:46:17.049
they were getting
it on, but no way

00:46:17.049 --> 00:46:18.340
is this happening in the movie.

00:46:18.340 --> 00:46:20.131
No way do you see Eddie
Murphy ever kissing

00:46:20.131 --> 00:46:22.390
a white woman in these movies.

00:46:22.390 --> 00:46:25.720
So you can how the restrictions
that were on black actors,

00:46:25.720 --> 00:46:26.221
definitely.

00:46:26.221 --> 00:46:28.595
And this is Eddie Murphy, who
was the most powerful actor

00:46:28.595 --> 00:46:29.260
in the '80s.

00:46:29.260 --> 00:46:30.430
So stuff like that.

00:46:30.430 --> 00:46:32.680
And of course the Ernie
Hudson thing in "Ghostbusters"

00:46:32.680 --> 00:46:34.370
is totally weird
and unacceptable.

00:46:34.370 --> 00:46:36.460
And I say that as someone who
loves "Ghostbusters" almost

00:46:36.460 --> 00:46:37.376
more than life itself.

00:46:37.376 --> 00:46:39.850
JON SKEET: Yeah, I remember
watching various films

00:46:39.850 --> 00:46:41.780
with my kids.

00:46:41.780 --> 00:46:44.835
So we have kids who
are 14, 11, and 11.

00:46:44.835 --> 00:46:46.210
It's like, "This
is a great film.

00:46:46.210 --> 00:46:46.830
Ignore that bit."

00:46:46.830 --> 00:46:47.700
HADLEY FREEMAN:
Ignore that bit, yeah.

00:46:47.700 --> 00:46:49.390
JON SKEET: Just ignore how
they're treating women.

00:46:49.390 --> 00:46:50.660
That's not how you treat women.

00:46:50.660 --> 00:46:52.180
HADLEY FREEMAN: Ignore that
really unfortunate bit.

00:46:52.180 --> 00:46:53.425
JON SKEET: But apart
from that, it's lovely.

00:46:53.425 --> 00:46:53.750
HADLEY FREEMAN: It's funny.

00:46:53.750 --> 00:46:55.670
John Hughes made
quite a few weirdly

00:46:55.670 --> 00:46:58.520
racist movies in his
kind of slapstick thing.

00:46:58.520 --> 00:47:03.500
Because he came from a
real slapstick tradition.

00:47:03.500 --> 00:47:06.260
So his movies, like the National
Lampoon's Vacation movies,

00:47:06.260 --> 00:47:09.324
which he wrote, are
so bizarrely racist.

00:47:09.324 --> 00:47:11.740
So there's this one scene, I
think it is in the first one,

00:47:11.740 --> 00:47:14.660
"National Lampoon's
Vacation," Chevy Chase

00:47:14.660 --> 00:47:18.260
is driving his kids
through the inner city.

00:47:18.260 --> 00:47:19.550
He lives in the suburbs.

00:47:19.550 --> 00:47:21.674
So he gets to the inner
city, which obviously means

00:47:21.674 --> 00:47:23.120
a street full of black people.

00:47:23.120 --> 00:47:26.089
And their car stops at a
light, I think, at this point,

00:47:26.089 --> 00:47:28.130
and loads of black people
just swarm in and start

00:47:28.130 --> 00:47:29.750
stealing their hubcaps.

00:47:29.750 --> 00:47:32.760
And in all of Hughes' movies--

00:47:32.760 --> 00:47:33.710
I love Hughes.

00:47:33.710 --> 00:47:36.370
Ferris Bueller is literally my
favorite movie of all time--

00:47:36.370 --> 00:47:37.880
the representation
of black people

00:47:37.880 --> 00:47:40.620
makes you just want to
throw up on your shoes.

00:47:40.620 --> 00:47:42.162
"Weird Science,"
for example, I don't

00:47:42.162 --> 00:47:44.411
know how many of you have
seen "Weird Science," that's

00:47:44.411 --> 00:47:46.190
also a terrible movie
in lots of ways.

00:47:46.190 --> 00:47:47.930
I mean, that's the
only other time

00:47:47.930 --> 00:47:49.360
you see black people
in a John Hughes movie.

00:47:49.360 --> 00:47:50.776
I'm trying to think
of any others.

00:47:50.776 --> 00:47:53.660
And it's when Anthony Michael
Hall goes to a jazz club,

00:47:53.660 --> 00:47:56.480
and there are loads
of jazz black people,

00:47:56.480 --> 00:47:58.700
all being kind of
creepy and jazz.

00:47:58.700 --> 00:47:59.420
And that's it.

00:47:59.420 --> 00:48:01.375
So in John Hughes'
world, black people

00:48:01.375 --> 00:48:04.490
are either stealing your hubcaps
or basically smoking reefer

00:48:04.490 --> 00:48:06.780
and being a bit creepy.

00:48:06.780 --> 00:48:11.054
So yeah, lots of bad stuff
but also lots of good stuff.

00:48:13.715 --> 00:48:15.340
AUDIENCE: So I'll
ask another question.

00:48:15.340 --> 00:48:16.430
[INAUDIBLE] You
