00:49:38.750 --> 00:49:40.833
HADLEY FREEMAN: It's very
weird when they do that.

00:49:43.010 --> 00:49:45.107
I make lists all the
time about '80s movies.

00:49:45.107 --> 00:49:46.940
I've already got a
stockpile of DVDs of what

00:49:46.940 --> 00:49:49.010
the kids are going to watch.

00:49:49.010 --> 00:49:53.120
So yes, "Back to the Future,"
"Indiana Jones," very much so.

00:49:53.120 --> 00:49:54.830
"Ferris Bueller,"
which I believe they

00:49:54.830 --> 00:49:56.960
will truly love at some point.

00:49:56.960 --> 00:49:59.000
And so on and so
forth like that.

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:02.285
"ET," Obviously "ET" might
be the first one even.

00:50:02.285 --> 00:50:04.910
JON SKEET: Do you know, I think
my kids got a bit bored by "ET"

00:50:04.910 --> 00:50:06.950
but loved "Ferris Bueller,"
loved "Back to the Future."

00:50:06.950 --> 00:50:08.330
HADLEY FREEMAN: Do you
know, I was scared by "ET"

00:50:08.330 --> 00:50:08.750
when I saw it.

00:50:08.750 --> 00:50:10.010
I think I saw it when
I was about seven,

00:50:10.010 --> 00:50:11.810
and I just thought
he was disgusting.

00:50:11.810 --> 00:50:16.032
And I was like, "Why is this
weird kind of tree trunk living

00:50:16.032 --> 00:50:17.240
in this little girl's closet?

00:50:17.240 --> 00:50:19.510
It's horrible."

00:50:19.510 --> 00:50:21.010
JON SKEET: But watch
Drew Barrymore.

00:50:21.010 --> 00:50:23.470
HADLEY FREEMAN: I know, I know.

00:50:23.470 --> 00:50:24.280
JON SKEET: Can we talk about
"Ferris Bueller" a bit more?

00:50:24.280 --> 00:50:25.270
HADLEY FREEMAN: Please!

00:50:25.270 --> 00:50:29.690
JON SKEET: So you talk about how
it's an interesting depiction.

00:50:29.690 --> 00:50:31.400
For one thing, I
love your take on it

00:50:31.400 --> 00:50:33.830
as a sort of fantasy, which
suddenly explains things,

00:50:33.830 --> 00:50:37.160
and it's one of those "Yeah,
why didn't I think of that?"

00:50:37.160 --> 00:50:38.937
But it talks a lot about class.

00:50:38.937 --> 00:50:39.770
HADLEY FREEMAN: Yes.

00:50:39.770 --> 00:50:42.920
JON SKEET: And I find the
whole class and wealth

00:50:42.920 --> 00:50:45.632
divides in films
interesting, particularly

00:50:45.632 --> 00:50:47.840
because it seems to be an
international difference as

00:50:47.840 --> 00:50:48.770
well.

00:50:48.770 --> 00:50:51.750
And I see it almost more
in soap operas, actually.

00:50:51.750 --> 00:50:53.745
So in the US, there's
"Dallas" and "Dynasty."

00:50:53.745 --> 00:50:54.440
HADLEY FREEMAN: Yeah, right.

00:50:54.440 --> 00:50:56.330
JON SKEET: In Australia, they're
sort of middle class, "Home

00:50:56.330 --> 00:50:57.460
and Away" and "Neighbors."

00:50:57.460 --> 00:50:59.793
HADLEY FREEMAN: I mean, one
of them, in "Home and Away,"

00:50:59.793 --> 00:51:02.044
I remember when I moved here,
they ran a trailer park.

00:51:02.044 --> 00:51:04.460
I can't remember what their
names were in "Home and Away,"

00:51:04.460 --> 00:51:06.692
but they're literally
over here "Eastenders."

00:51:06.692 --> 00:51:08.150
I couldn't believe
the differences.

00:51:08.150 --> 00:51:10.560
JON SKEET: There's now middle
class, upper middle class

00:51:10.560 --> 00:51:12.230
in Australia.

00:51:12.230 --> 00:51:14.810
And then we have "Eastenders"
and "Coronation Street."

00:51:14.810 --> 00:51:19.150
And if you look at a lot of
the UK film industry output,

00:51:19.150 --> 00:51:21.020
things like "Brassed
Off," "Billy Elliot,"

00:51:21.020 --> 00:51:25.250
tends to be more working class
and will focus on the class

00:51:25.250 --> 00:51:25.940
divide more.

00:51:25.940 --> 00:51:26.300
HADLEY FREEMAN: Yeah.

00:51:26.300 --> 00:51:27.758
JON SKEET: So I
find it interesting

00:51:27.758 --> 00:51:30.470
how "Ferris Bueller's Day Off"
focuses is on the class divide

00:51:30.470 --> 00:51:33.510
but between upper middle class
and really, really, rich.

00:51:33.510 --> 00:51:36.500
HADLEY FREEMAN: Yeah, for sure.

00:51:36.500 --> 00:51:38.650
JON SKEET: And that
feels like wealth

00:51:38.650 --> 00:51:42.230
as a proxy for
structure versus agency.

00:51:42.230 --> 00:51:43.070
HADLEY FREEMAN: Yes.

00:51:43.070 --> 00:51:46.370
JON SKEET: Which
I only found out,

00:51:46.370 --> 00:51:48.590
learned about as terms
reading "Girls Will Be

00:51:48.590 --> 00:51:49.797
Girls" by Emer O'Toole.

00:51:49.797 --> 00:51:50.880
HADLEY FREEMAN: Very good.

00:51:50.880 --> 00:51:52.254
JON SKEET: Awesome,
awesome book.

00:51:52.254 --> 00:51:54.250
Go read.

00:51:54.250 --> 00:51:56.500
What films should I
have watched to talk

00:51:56.500 --> 00:51:58.294
about structure versus agency?

00:51:58.294 --> 00:52:00.460
HADLEY FREEMAN: I mean, to
me, the most obvious film

00:52:00.460 --> 00:52:03.460
about class is actually a
slightly earlier John Hughes

00:52:03.460 --> 00:52:05.500
film, which is "Pretty
in Pink," which

00:52:05.500 --> 00:52:09.760
is very much about working
class kids versus the rich kids.

00:52:09.760 --> 00:52:11.620
John Hughes himself
was lower middle class,

00:52:11.620 --> 00:52:13.480
and he grew up in an upper
middle class neighborhood

00:52:13.480 --> 00:52:14.690
in the suburbs of Illinois.

00:52:14.690 --> 00:52:16.690
So he was always very
self-conscious about class

00:52:16.690 --> 00:52:17.590
differences.

00:52:17.590 --> 00:52:20.500
And in his movie, the rich
kids are always kind of evil,

00:52:20.500 --> 00:52:22.846
and the poor kids are noble.

00:52:22.846 --> 00:52:24.220
But the rich kids
get everything,

00:52:24.220 --> 00:52:26.770
and the poor kids
have to struggle.

00:52:26.770 --> 00:52:28.300
And when he made
"Ferris Bueller,"

00:52:28.300 --> 00:52:30.070
he kind of recreated that.

00:52:30.070 --> 00:52:32.200
So "Pretty in Pink,"
there's a character,

00:52:32.200 --> 00:52:35.085
Duckie, played by Jon Cryer,
who is very working class,

00:52:35.085 --> 00:52:36.960
sleeps on apparently a
mattress on the floor,

00:52:36.960 --> 00:52:40.060
and seems to not
have any parents.

00:52:40.060 --> 00:52:42.280
And he is up against
the horrible rich kids

00:52:42.280 --> 00:52:44.470
in school, played
by James Spader,

00:52:44.470 --> 00:52:47.720
ultimate crush, who is
this kind of awful drugs,

00:52:47.720 --> 00:52:50.740
taking obnoxious guy called
"Steff" for some reason.

00:52:50.740 --> 00:52:53.500
All characters in John Hughes
movies have really weird names.

00:52:53.500 --> 00:52:54.730
One day, I want to
do a dissertion.

00:52:54.730 --> 00:52:56.938
I want to go back to school
and do a PhD dissertation

00:52:56.938 --> 00:52:59.580
on the names of kids
in John Hughes' movies.

00:52:59.580 --> 00:53:00.970
Anyway, so there's Steff.

00:53:00.970 --> 00:53:05.620
So anyway, Duckie is unpopular
because basically he's poor.

00:53:05.620 --> 00:53:07.246
That's what "Pretty
in Pink" is saying.

00:53:07.246 --> 00:53:09.328
And the same for Molly
Ringwald's character, Andy.

00:53:09.328 --> 00:53:10.855
She's unpopular
because she's poor.

00:53:10.855 --> 00:53:12.730
I mean, she literally
lives on the wrong side

00:53:12.730 --> 00:53:13.563
of the train tracks.

00:53:13.563 --> 00:53:16.000
They have her living next
to a train, for god's sake.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:18.070
So when he came to
write "Ferris Bueller,"

00:53:18.070 --> 00:53:21.170
he rewrote Duckie
but as a fantasy.

00:53:21.170 --> 00:53:23.930
And he got Matthew Broderick to
play the character of Ferris.

00:53:23.930 --> 00:53:26.670
And Matthew Broderick and
Jon Cryer as teenagers

00:53:26.670 --> 00:53:28.420
look basically identical.

00:53:28.420 --> 00:53:30.270
JON SKEET: Particularly
in the parade scene.

00:53:30.270 --> 00:53:31.270
HADLEY FREEMAN: Exactly.

00:53:31.270 --> 00:53:35.140
I mean, with the coif,
he's basically Duckie.

00:53:35.140 --> 00:53:38.050
But he made Ferris Bueller
upper middle class,

00:53:38.050 --> 00:53:39.250
and lives in this big house.

00:53:39.250 --> 00:53:40.750
And he made him
exactly like Duckie.

00:53:40.750 --> 00:53:42.550
He likes weird British bands.

00:53:42.550 --> 00:53:44.710
He wears weird two-tone shoes.

00:53:44.710 --> 00:53:45.910
He knows about tech.

00:53:45.910 --> 00:53:48.670
He's quite annoying,
but everyone loves him.

00:53:48.670 --> 00:53:50.115
JON SKEET: Those aren't related,
by the way, knowing about tech

00:53:50.115 --> 00:53:50.906
and being annoying.

00:53:53.945 --> 00:53:55.570
HADLEY FREEMAN: Read
the room, Freeman!

00:53:59.475 --> 00:54:00.850
But they make him
really popular,

00:54:00.850 --> 00:54:02.560
and everyone in
the town loves him.

00:54:02.560 --> 00:54:05.854
And so it's kind of Duckie/John
Hughes' fantasy of what

00:54:05.854 --> 00:54:07.270
he could have been
like, what life

00:54:07.270 --> 00:54:08.895
could have been like
if he'd been rich.

00:54:08.895 --> 00:54:10.894
And he could have skipped
school and gotten away

00:54:10.894 --> 00:54:11.730
with everything.

00:54:11.730 --> 00:54:13.188
If he stayed home
from school sick,

00:54:13.188 --> 00:54:15.672
there'd be banners in the
sky saying "Get well soon."

00:54:15.672 --> 00:54:16.630
All that kind of stuff.

00:54:16.630 --> 00:54:19.330
It's a real teenager's
fantasy of popularity.

00:54:19.330 --> 00:54:23.019
And for John Hughes, popularity
and wealth were synonymous.

00:54:23.019 --> 00:54:25.060
I think it is interesting
when British people see

00:54:25.060 --> 00:54:27.580
American movies that show
social class divides,

00:54:27.580 --> 00:54:29.404
because British
poverty and America

00:54:29.404 --> 00:54:31.445
in poverty in a lot of
ways are really different.

00:54:31.445 --> 00:54:34.776
A really interesting
illustration of that for me

00:54:34.776 --> 00:54:36.400
was when I went to
see "Blue Valentine"

00:54:36.400 --> 00:54:39.090
a few years ago in this
country with some friends.

00:54:39.090 --> 00:54:41.650
And "Blue Valentine" starring
Michelle Williams and Ryan

00:54:41.650 --> 00:54:43.589
Gosling, I'm sure a lot
of you have seen it,

00:54:43.589 --> 00:54:45.880
I mean they're supposed to
be quite poor in that movie.

00:54:45.880 --> 00:54:47.050
I mean, that's part
of the movie is,

00:54:47.050 --> 00:54:48.490
they're struggling with money.

00:54:48.490 --> 00:54:50.397
But they always
have massive cars.

00:54:50.397 --> 00:54:52.230
And I didn't even notice
this when I saw it,

00:54:52.230 --> 00:54:54.250
but when I came out my best
friend who's British was like,

00:54:54.250 --> 00:54:56.749
"If they're so poor, why are
they driving these massive four

00:54:56.749 --> 00:54:57.730
by fours?"

00:54:57.730 --> 00:55:00.070
And I was like, "You see,
in America, obviously,

00:55:00.070 --> 00:55:02.200
there's a whole thing
about American-like--"

00:55:02.200 --> 00:55:05.050
basically, I don't even
know what they call it now.

00:55:05.050 --> 00:55:06.490
It's leasing cars.

00:55:06.490 --> 00:55:07.907
And in American
suburbs, everybody

00:55:07.907 --> 00:55:10.531
has these massive cars that they
lease, and they're going poor.

00:55:10.531 --> 00:55:13.130
And that's not saying British
poverty and American poverty,

00:55:13.130 --> 00:55:13.520
I don't know.

00:55:13.520 --> 00:55:14.890
It's not like American
people aren't poor.

00:55:14.890 --> 00:55:16.070
British people aren't poor.

00:55:16.070 --> 00:55:16.930
It's just a different attitude.

00:55:16.930 --> 00:55:18.721
So a lot of times in
these American movies,

00:55:18.721 --> 00:55:21.220
I feel like British people
see people with massive cars

00:55:21.220 --> 00:55:22.600
and think "Oh, they're
not really poor,"

00:55:22.600 --> 00:55:24.790
and actually it's a whole
different kind of weird poverty

00:55:24.790 --> 00:55:25.690
system in America.

00:55:25.690 --> 00:55:27.700
Anyway, that's a
different thing.

00:55:27.700 --> 00:55:30.102
But also the big
houses in these movies,

00:55:30.102 --> 00:55:32.560
that's another thing that I
find British people find really

00:55:32.560 --> 00:55:34.780
weirded out by, particularly
the suburban houses

00:55:34.780 --> 00:55:36.130
in John Hughes' movies.

00:55:36.130 --> 00:55:38.290
Like, you look at the
house in "Home Alone."

00:55:38.290 --> 00:55:40.640
I mean, the house seems
as big as the White House.

00:55:40.640 --> 00:55:43.150
I mean, the house
is freaking massive.

00:55:43.150 --> 00:55:45.209
But the truth is,
in the suburbs,

00:55:45.209 --> 00:55:46.750
they are probably
very expensive now,

00:55:46.750 --> 00:55:49.780
but there are a lot of bigger
houses that don't necessarily

00:55:49.780 --> 00:55:52.510
denote massive wealth,
that they would especially

00:55:52.510 --> 00:55:53.880
here in the countryside.

00:55:53.880 --> 00:55:57.160
I mean, you can get these big
houses in the suburbs things

00:55:57.160 --> 00:56:00.378
that don't require you
to be a billionaire.

